`src/pages/Library.tsx:29-33` and `src/lib/progress.ts:32-39`

Every `BookCard` calls `useAllProgress()` — the whole progress store, not just its own book's slice. `store.set` always returns a **new top-level object** (`{...s, [bookId]: ...}`), so `useSyncExternalStore` fires a change for *every* subscriber whenever *any* book's progress updates. Marking one chapter read re-renders every card in the library.

```tsx
// current — subscribes to the entire store
function BookCard({ book, step }: { book: Book; step?: number }) {
  const all = useAllProgress()
  const progress = all[book.id]
  ...
```

Fix: add a selector-based hook so each card only re-renders when its own slice changes, and memoize the card itself.

```ts
// progress.ts
export function useBookProgressSelector<T>(bookId: string, select: (p: BookProgress) => T): T {
  return useSyncExternalStore(store.subscribe, () => select(sanitize(store.get()[bookId])))
}
```

```tsx
const BookCard = memo(function BookCard({ book, step }: { book: Book; step?: number }) {
  const pct = useBookProgressSelector(book.id, (p) => completionPct(book.map.chapters.length, p))
  ...
})
```

`src/lib/content.ts:161-170`, called from `BookCard`, `BookMap`, and `ContinueStrip`

`bookStats` does several `reduce`s over `map.chapters` plus regex-based `countWords`. It's pure given `book`, but nothing memoizes it — it reruns on every render of every card (compounded by finding #1: a single progress update re-runs it for *all* books). Wrap with a `WeakMap`/id cache or `useMemo` at the call site:

```ts
const statsCache = new Map<string, BookStats>()
export function bookStats(b: Book): BookStats {
  const cached = statsCache.get(b.id)
  if (cached) return cached
  const stats = computeStats(b) // existing body
  statsCache.set(b.id, stats)
  return stats
}
```
Safe because `books` is static content loaded once at build/module time — never mutated at runtime.

`src/lib/content.ts`:
- `categoryOf(book)` → `categories.find(c => c.id === book.categoryId)` — called once per book, per render (Library renders all books).
- `booksInCategory(categoryId)` → `books.filter(...)` — called once per category **on every Library render** (`src/pages/Library.tsx:199`), each doing a full pass over `books`.

For N books and M categories, rendering the Library is O(N·M) work that's trivially O(N) with precomputed indexes:

```ts
const categoryById = new Map(categories.map((c) => [c.id, c]))
export function categoryOf(book: Book) { return categoryById.get(book.categoryId) }

const booksByCategory = new Map<string, Book[]>()
for (const b of books) {
  const list = booksByCategory.get(b.categoryId) ?? []
  list.push(b)
  booksByCategory.set(b.categoryId, list)
}
export function booksInCategory(categoryId: string) { return booksByCategory.get(categoryId) ?? [] }
```
Small dataset today, but this scales linearly with content and currently reruns on *every* keystroke-triggered re-render of `Library` (see #4), not just once.

`src/pages/Library.tsx:95` + `src/lib/content.ts:182-193`

```tsx
const results = useMemo(() => searchBooks(query), [query])
```
`useMemo` here only prevents *duplicate* recompute per render, not per-keystroke work — every keystroke still re-scans all books × chapters × categoryOf lookups. Fine at 10s of books; add a `useDeferredValue`/debounce once the catalog grows, since typing fast currently triggers a full re-score on every character:

```tsx
const deferredQuery = useDeferredValue(query)
const results = useMemo(() => searchBooks(deferredQuery), [deferredQuery])
```

`src/lib/content.ts:120-150` (`loadChapter`)

Every time `Reader` mounts for a chapter (including navigating back and forth, or React StrictMode's double-invoke in dev), `loadChapter` re-runs the regex parsing **and** re-runs `marked.parse` (`mdToHtml`) from scratch — same input, same output, every time. This is the most expensive per-visit computation in the app (markdown parsing) and is fully cacheable since chapter files are static.

```ts
const chapterCache = new Map<string, Promise<Chapter | null>>()
export function loadChapter(bookId: string, n: number): Promise<Chapter | null> {
  const key = `${bookId}/${n}`
  let p = chapterCache.get(key)
  if (!p) {
    p = loadChapterUncached(bookId, n)
    chapterCache.set(key, p)
  }
  return p
}
```
Caching the in-flight promise also collapses concurrent double-fetches (e.g. StrictMode).

`src/pages/Reader.tsx` (`onScroll` effect)

```tsx
const onScroll = () => {
  const el = document.documentElement
  const max = el.scrollHeight - window.innerHeight
  setPct(max > 0 ? Math.min(100, (window.scrollY / max) * 100) : 100)
}
window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true })
```
This calls `setState` on *every* scroll event (can fire dozens of times/sec), triggering a re-render of the whole `Reader` tree each time, and it isn't wrapped in `requestAnimationFrame`. Throttle via rAF:

```tsx
const onScroll = () => {
  requestAnimationFrame(() => {
    const max = document.documentElement.scrollHeight - window.innerHeight
    setPct(max > 0 ? Math.min(100, (window.scrollY / max) * 100) : 100)
  })
}
```
Also worth moving the progress bar's width into a ref-driven DOM write (bypass React state) if this needs to feel perfectly smooth, since it's purely visual.

